\begin_layout Title
Auctions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In an auction, a single seller tries to sell one unit of some commodity
 to one of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 different buyers.
 Only one buyer can buy the unit.
 The seller's problem is to decide who to sell it to, and how much to charge
 them.
 We'll imagine that sellers are risk neutral expected revenue maximizers.
 They just want to sell the good in a way that will maximize their expected
 revenue.
 Buyers are interested in the difference between what an object is worth
 to them, and what they have to pay for it.
 They want to maximize the product of the probability that they win the
 auction times the difference between their value and what they expect to
 pay for the good when they win.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The thing that makes everyone's problem hard is that no one knows any of
 the buyers' values.
 It is a game of incomplete information.
 In everything that follows, we'll make the assumption that values are identical
ly and independently distributed.
 To keep things simple, lets just suppose that this distribution has its
 support on the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

, meaning that if 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is the probability that a certain bidder's valuation is less than or equal
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(0\right)=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(1\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
 Otherwise, lets suppose this distribution has a density given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This means, of course, that 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)=\int_{0}^{x}f\left(t\right)dt$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The idea here is that each bidder believes that each of the other bidders
 has a value that is somewhere between 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, and that 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is the probability that this value is less than or equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Second price auction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a sealed bid second price auction, each bidder submits a bid to the seller.
 The seller then chooses the bidder who submits the highest bid, and offers
 him the good at a price which is equal to the second highest bid that was
 submitted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we argued, the bidder can't affect the price he pays by changing his
 bid.
 The price he pays is the bid that someone else submitted.
 However, he can affect the probability that he wins by raising or lowering
 his bid.
 If his bid is lower than his value, he will raise the probability of winning
 the auction by increasing his bid.
 This would be good, because he will be better off whenever he wins the
 auction while paying something less than his value.
 On the other hand, if his bid is above his value, then he is inevitably
 doing to win sometimes and pay more for the good than it is actually worth
 to him.
 For that reason, he would be better off lowering his bid.
 We decided that the bid 
\begin_inset Formula $b\left(v\right)$
\end_inset

 that maximizes the expected payoff for a buyer whose value is 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is just 
\begin_inset Formula $b\left(v\right)=v$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lets check some of the implications of this.
 The first is just the bidder who wins in this case is just the bidder with
 the highest value.
 So if a bidder wants to figure out how likely it is he or she will win
 in equilibrium, they just compute the probability that their value is highest.
 This is the probability that each of the other bidders has a lower value
 than they do, and this is just 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(v\right)^{n-1}$
\end_inset

.
 So the probability they win the auction when their value is 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is going to be 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(v\right)^{n-1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What are they likely to pay if they win? This is the expectation of the
 highest value of the other bidders, conditional on the other bidders having
 values lower than 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

.
 This is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\left(n-1\right)\int_{0}^{v}\tilde{v}F^{n-2}\left(\tilde{v}\right)f\left(\tilde{v}\right)d\tilde{v}}{F^{n-1}\left(v\right)}.\label{expected-payment}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Lets go over this calculation.
 Pick one of the other bidders, say bidder 1, and imagine that his value
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{v}$
\end_inset

.
 This event occurs with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\tilde{v}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 In that case, the probability that all the others have lower values than
 his is 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(\tilde{v}\right)^{n-2}$
\end_inset

, because there are 
\begin_inset Formula $n-2$
\end_inset

 bidders other than you and bidder 1.
 Of course, it could also have been bidder 2 who had this value 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Summing this up over the 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

 bidders other than yourself, this says that the probability that the highest
 value bidder among the others has value 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{v}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(n-1\right)F\left(\tilde{v}\right)^{n-2}f\left(\tilde{v}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we want to use Bayes rule.
 You know that your value is 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

.
 So the joint probability that your value is 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 and the highest among the others is 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{v}$
\end_inset

 is just 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(n-1\right)F\left(\tilde{v}\right)^{n-2}f\left(\tilde{v}\right)$
\end_inset

, as we just calculated as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{v}<v$
\end_inset

.
 For Bayes rule, we then need to divide by the probability that your value
 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is highest, which is just 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{n-1}\left(v\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We then take the expectation using this conditional probability distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In words, we just decided that the amount you should expect to pay if your
 value is 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 in a second price auction is given by (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "expected-payment"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Work out the expected payment when there are 2 other bidders and 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is uniform (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)=x$
\end_inset

).
 Now do the same when there are three other bidders.
 How does the amount you expect to pay change between 2 and 3 other bidders?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Answer question 1 again, but assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)=x^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 What impact does this change in the distribution have.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Why worry about the expected payment?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If you bid in a second price auction, you will do okay as long as you don't
 bid more than your value.
 In a way, there isn't really much reason to do the calculation we did above.
 However, it is an important calculation for the seller.
 Lets do the calculation from the seller's point of view.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is the highest value among the bidders in the auction.
 Then the revenue that the seller should expect to get from the bidder who
 wins the auction is exactly what that bidder expects to pay, i.e., the expression
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "expected-payment"

\end_inset

).
 The probability that bidder 1 is the high bidder and has value 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\left(v\right)F^{n-1}\left(v\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Multiply that by the revenue the seller expects to earn from bidder 1 when
 he is high bidder with value 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 and you get
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(n-1\right)\int_{0}^{v}\tilde{v}F^{n-2}\left(\tilde{v}\right)f\left(\tilde{v}\right)d\tilde{v}f\left(v\right).
\]

\end_inset

Now integrate this over all the possible values bidder 1 could have, then
 multiply it by 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 because there are 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 bidders in all, and you get the revenue the seller expects to get from
 the second price auction
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
n\int_{0}^{1}\left(n-1\right)\left\{ \int_{0}^{v}\tilde{v}F^{n-2}\left(\tilde{v}\right)f\left(\tilde{v}\right)d\tilde{v}\right\} f\left(v\right)dv.\label{second-price-revenue}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Calculate expected revenue when 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(v\right)=v$
\end_inset

 and show that it is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\left(n-1\right)}{n}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
First Price Auctions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is interesting that second price auctions have an equilibrium where bidders
 bid their true values.
 Yet one might wonder whether there might not be better ways to sell something.
 For example, imagine that you are trying to sell some public land to make
 money for taxpayers.
 You decide to hold a second price auction.
 Some big company gives you a bid of $1 million.
 By what we have just said, that is the amount the company thinks the land
 is worth.
 Why not just charge them $1 million - that seems better for taxpayers.
 After all, why deliberately charge the company something less than what
 you know they are willing to pay.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The answer is that if they know you are going to do this, they won't bid
 $1 million, they will bid something considerably less.
 If you want to figure out if it would be better to charge them what they
 bid, you need to figure out exactly what they will bid.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To do this we can use an unusual conceptual approach.
 Suppose that we guess that the companies will use a common bidding rule
 
\begin_inset Formula $b\left(v\right)$
\end_inset

.
 What they bid will depend on their value, which we don't know, but if two
 firms have the same value, then we expect they will submit the same bid.
 Lets also assume that whatever this bidding rule is, it is monotonically
 increasing.
 Suppose there are 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 companies bidding on the land and take the perspective of any one of them.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since it is a first price auction, it is much simpler to figure out what
 the company will pay if it wins - just whatever it chose to bid.
 So we really only have to figure out how to find the probability they win
 with each bid.
 Suppose the company decides to bid 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{\prime}$
\end_inset

.
 Then if it thinks the other firms are using the bidding rule 
\begin_inset Formula $b\left(v\right)$
\end_inset

, it expects to beat any of the other firms who bid less than 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{\prime}.$
\end_inset

 Since the bidding rule is monotonic, they should bid less than 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $b\left(\tilde{v}\right)<b^{\prime}$
\end_inset

.
 So what we need to do is to figure out what value a firm would need to
 have to make them bid 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{\prime}.$
\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $b\left(v\right)$
\end_inset

 is strictly increasing, this value is 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{-1}\left(b^{\prime}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But that means that the bid 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 will win the auction if all the other bidders have values less than or
 equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{-1}\left(b^{\prime}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This probability is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F^{n-1}\left(b^{-1}\left(b^{\prime}\right)\right).
\]

\end_inset

So a bidder with value 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 needs to maximize
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(v-b^{\prime}\right)F^{n-1}\left(b^{-1}\left(b^{\prime}\right)\right).
\]

\end_inset

Now we can use a trick.
 If the bidding function 
\begin_inset Formula $b\left(v\right)$
\end_inset

 is an equilibrium, then 
\begin_inset Formula $b\left(v\right)$
\end_inset

 will maximize the function above for a bidder with value 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

.
 One way to say this is that bidder 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 would rather submit the bid 
\begin_inset Formula $b\left(v\right)$
\end_inset

 than the bid that would be submitted by a bidder with some other value,
 say 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\prime}$
\end_inset

.
 That is, in a Bayes Nash equilibrium, bidder 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 should prefer to bid 
\begin_inset Formula $b\left(v\right)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $b\left(v^{\prime}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We don't know exactly what a bidder with value 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 will bid, but whatever it is, it will win if all the other bidders have
 values less than 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 because of the fact the bidding rule is monotonic.
 So the bidding rule should satisfy
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(v-b\left(v\right)\right)F^{n-1}\left(v\right)\ge\left(v-b\left(v^{\prime}\right)\right)F^{n-1}\left(v^{\prime}\right)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\prime}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, that means that the derivative of the function 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(v-b\left(v^{\prime}\right)\right)F^{n-1}\left(v^{\prime}\right)
\]

\end_inset

with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\prime}$
\end_inset

should be zero when 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\prime}=v$
\end_inset

.
 In other words
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(v-b\left(v\right)\right)\left(n-1\right)F^{n-2}\left(v\right)f\left(v\right)=b^{\prime}\left(v\right)F^{n-1}\left(v\right).\label{foc}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One way we could approach this is to solve for 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b^{\prime}\left(v\right)=\frac{\left(v-b\left(v\right)\right)\left(n-1\right)f\left(v\right)}{F\left(v\right)}.
\]

\end_inset

If you observe that must hold for every value of 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

, it becomes a differential equation that we could try to solve.
 However, there is another way to get the solution that will help in our
 comparison to the second price auction.
 Lets just rewrite (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "foc"

\end_inset

) as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v\left(n-1\right)F^{n-2}\left(v\right)f\left(v\right)=b\left(v\right)\left(n-1\right)F^{n-2}\left(v\right)f\left(v\right)+b^{\prime}\left(v\right)F^{n-1}\left(v\right).
\]

\end_inset

Now observe that the right hand side of this expression is just the derivative
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $b\left(v\right)F^{n-1}\left(v\right)$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What that means is that uniformly in 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\left\{ b\left(v\right)F^{n-1}\left(v\right)\right\} }{dv}=v\left(n-1\right)F^{n-2}\left(v\right)f\left(v\right).
\]

\end_inset

Then we just use the fundamental theorem of calculus, and integrate the
 derivative to get the function itself, i.e.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b\left(v\right)F^{n-1}\left(v\right)=\int_{0}^{v}\tilde{v}\left(n-1\right)F^{n-2}\left(\tilde{v}\right)f\left(\tilde{v}\right)d\tilde{v},
\]

\end_inset

or
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b\left(v\right)=\frac{\int_{0}^{v}\tilde{v}\left(n-1\right)F^{n-2}\left(\tilde{v}\right)f\left(\tilde{v}\right)d\tilde{v}}{F^{n-1}\left(v\right)}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now you can look back at the expression we got in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "expected-payment"

\end_inset

) describing the amount that a bidder in the second price auction expects
 to pay conditional on winning - you will see it is exactly the same.
 The stunning conclusion is that the amount that the seller should expect
 to receive from the winning bidder is exactly the same in both the first
 and second price auctions.
 They produce exactly the same revenue.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
All Pay Auctions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If you don't find the relationship between the first and second price auction
 surprising, here is an even more surprising result.
 Many auctions (or at least things that act like auctions) have the property
 that the high bidder wins the auction and pays whatever she bid.
 Yet everyone else in the auction has to pay what they bid as well.
 If you think that sounds unreasonable, that is in many ways what happens
 in education.
 To get a job you spend a lot of money on education - the most educated
 person gets the most desirable job.
 If you don't get the most desirable job, you still have to pay for the
 education you received.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Many kinds of litigation are like this.
 One party sues the other, then both lawyer up.
 The side that spends the most on lawyers wins the case, but both sides
 have to pay their lawyers.
\begin_inset Foot
