\begin_layout Plain Layout
An interesting example of this kind of thing that pertains to another part
 of this course is the companies that act as 'patent trolls'.
 The way patent trolls work is to apply for, or buy very vague patents,
 then suing a company for patent violation.
 Even if the patent doesn't apply, the company who is being sued has to
 defend itself in court, which requires them to lawyer up in the manner
 described above.
 The patent troll then offers to settle out of court for an upfront payment,
 which the company will normally pay.
 This is type of extortion which is perfectly legal under US 
\emph on
intellectual property 
\emph default
law.
 If you are getting bored with auctions, here is a story about patent trolls
 - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3bxcc3SM_KA
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can find an equilibrium for this sort of thing using the approach above.
 Lets suppose the bidders use a monotonic rule 
\begin_inset Formula $b\left(v\right)$
\end_inset

 to decide how much to bid.
 Once again, if 
\begin_inset Formula $b\left(v\right)$
\end_inset

 is a Bayesian equilibrium bidding rule, then the function
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
vF^{n-1}\left(v^{\prime}\right)-b\left(v^{\prime}\right)
\]

\end_inset

should be maximized when 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{\prime}=v$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The corresponding first order condition is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v\left(n-1\right)F^{n-2}\left(v\right)f\left(v\right)=b^{\prime}\left(v\right).
\]

\end_inset

This is actually really easy because we can use the fundamental rule of
 calculus right away to get
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b\left(v\right)=\int_{0}^{v}\tilde{v}\left(n-1\right)F^{n-2}\left(\tilde{v}\right)f\left(\tilde{v}\right)d\tilde{v}.
\]

\end_inset

If you compare this to the bid in the first price auction, it is much smaller.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, the total expected payments to the seller are
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n\int_{0}^{1}b\left(v\right)f\left(v\right)dv=
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n\int_{0}^{1}\int_{0}^{v}\tilde{v}\left(n-1\right)F^{n-2}\left(\tilde{v}\right)f\left(\tilde{v}\right)d\tilde{v}f\left(v\right)dv.
\]

\end_inset

 If you compare this to our original formula for the revenue in the second
 price auction, given by (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "second-price-revenue"

\end_inset

), you will see that it is exactly the same.
\end_layout

